# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cortlandt-new-york
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1790-united-states-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1820-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] The Bear Mountain Bridge Road and Toll House and the Old Croton Dam are listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] The Cortlandt area is known for its Revolutionary War history, specifically the location of the strategic **King's Ferry** between Stony Point and Verplanck's Point, which George Washington's army used to cross the Hudson on its march to Yorktown, Virginia, in 1781.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] John Trumbull's full-length oil portrait of *Washington at Verplanck's Point* exists in two versions.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] The town's western borders are the Hudson River and the city of Peekskill.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] Its northern borders are the towns of Philipstown and Putnam Valley in Putnam County.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] Its eastern border is the town of Yorktown.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] Its southern borders are the towns of New Castle and Ossining.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] According to the United States Census Bureau, the town has a total area of 50.0 square miles (129.5 km2), of which 39.3 square miles (101.7 km2) is land and 10.8 square miles (27.9 km2), or 21.51%, is water.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] At the 2000 census there were 38,467 people in 13,517 households, including 10,137 families, in the town.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] The population density was 969.7 inhabitants per square mile (374.4/km2).
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] There were 14,065 housing units at an average density of 354.5 units per square mile (136.9 units/km2).
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] The racial makeup of the town was 88.60% White, 4.59% African American, 0.21% Native American, 2.57% Asian, 0.01% Pacific Islander, 2.35% from other races, and 1.68% from two or more races.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 7.19%.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] Of the 13,517 households 39.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 64.3% were married couples living together, 7.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 25.0% were non-families.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] 21.3% of households were one person and 8.8% were one person aged 65 or older.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] The average household size was 2.75 and the average family size was 3.22.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] For every 100 females, there were 95.8 males.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 92.7 males.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] The median household income was $75,442 and the median family income was $89,053.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] Males had a median income of $59,949 versus $41,115 for females.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] The per capita income for the town was $33,432.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] About 2.9% of families and 4.5% of the population were below the poverty line, including 4.1% of those under age 18 and 5.1% of those age 65 or over.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] Commuter service to New York City is available via the Cortlandt train station and the Croton-Harmon train station, served by Metro-North Railroad.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] Route 9 passes through the town along the Hudson River side.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] The Appalachian Trail (AT) runs through a very small portion of the north west portion of the town near and over the Bear Mountain Bridge, which is the only section of the AT in Westchester County NY.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] Cortlandt is governed by a town board and the Town Supervisor is Dr.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] Richard Becker, who replaced Linda Puglisi as the longest-serving Town Supervisor in the 200+-year history of the town (30 years).
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] The mayors of Buchanan and Croton are Theresa Knickerbocker and Brian Pugh, respectively.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] Law enforcement services in Cortlandt are provided by the New York State Police and the Westchester County Department of Public Safety.
[src:cortlandt-new-york/cortlandt-new-york] The villages of Buchanan and Croton-on-Hudson also have their own, independent police departments.
